                 <table>
                  <tr>
                   <td class="statText" colspan="2">
                    There are 10 bags and we only have 2 turns to find the correct one.
We can easily convince ourselves that fewer than 3 friends are not enough in this case.
                    <br/>
                    Here is one possible strategy that uses three friends:
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                    Let's label the bags 1 through 10.
                    <br/>
                    In the first turn, give pills from bags {1,2,3} to the first friend, pills from {4,5,6} to the second friend, and pills from {7,8,9} to the third one.
After the first turn, there are two possibilities:
                    <br/>
                    If neither of them disappeared into the Matrix, bag 10 has to be the one with the magic pills.
                    <br/>
                    The other case is that one of them disappeared.
Without loss of generality, suppose that the first friend is now in the Matrix.
We know that the magic pills are in one of the bags 1, 2, and 3.
We also still have the two other friends who did not disappear.
In the second round, we give a pill from bag 1 to one of them and a pill from bag 2 to the other.
                   </td>
                  </tr>
                 </table>
                </td>
               </tr>
              </table>
